### Initialize and Run Agent with Gemini Model in Go

Source: https://context7.com/google/adk-go/llms.txt

Demonstrates initializing a Gemini model, creating an agent, setting up necessary services (session, artifact, memory), and configuring a runner. It then shows how to create a session and execute the agent with a user message, processing both final responses and function calls.

```go
package main

import (
    "context"
    "fmt"
    "log"
    "os"

    "google.golang.org/genai"
    "google.golang.org/adk/agent"
    "google.golang.org/adk/agent/llmagent"
    "google.golang.org/adk/artifact"
    "google.golang.org/adk/memory"
    "google.golang.org/adk/model/gemini"
    "google.golang.org/adk/runner"
    "google.golang.org/adk/session"
)

func main() {
    ctx := context.Background()

    model, _ := gemini.NewModel(ctx, "gemini-2.5-flash", &genai.ClientConfig{
        APIKey: os.Getenv("GOOGLE_API_KEY"),
    })

    myAgent, _ := llmagent.New(llmagent.Config{
        Name:        "assistant",
        Model:       model,
        Description: "Helpful assistant",
        Instruction: "You are a helpful assistant.",
    })

    // Create services
    sessionService := session.InMemoryService()
    artifactService := artifact.InMemoryService()
    memoryService := memory.InMemoryService()

    // Create runner with all services
    r, err := runner.New(runner.Config{
        AppName:         "my_app",
        Agent:           myAgent,
        SessionService:  sessionService,
        ArtifactService: artifactService, // Optional
        MemoryService:   memoryService,   // Optional
    })
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("Failed to create runner: %v", err)
    }

    // Create a session
    sessResp, _ := sessionService.Create(ctx, &session.CreateRequest{
        AppName: "my_app",
        UserID:  "user123",
    })

    // Run agent with user message
    userMsg := genai.NewContentFromText("What is the capital of France?", genai.RoleUser)

    for event, err := range r.Run(ctx, "user123", sessResp.Session.ID(), userMsg, agent.RunConfig{
        StreamingMode: agent.StreamingModeNone, // or StreamingModeSSE for streaming
    }) {
        if err != nil {
            log.Printf("Error: %v", err)
            continue
        }

        // Process events
        if event.IsFinalResponse() {
            if event.Content != nil {
                for _, part := range event.Content.Parts {
                    if part.Text != "" {
                        fmt.Printf("Final Response: %s\n", part.Text)
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        // Check for function calls
        if event.Content != nil {
            for _, part := range event.Content.Parts {
                if part.FunctionCall != nil {
                    fmt.Printf("Tool called: %s\n", part.FunctionCall.Name)
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Agent Development Kit (ADK) for Go > Creating an LLM Agent

Source: https://context7.com/google/adk-go/llms.txt

The `llmagent.New()` function creates an LLM-powered agent that can use tools, follow instructions, and interact with users. This is the primary way to create AI agents in ADK.

--------------------------------

### Model Callbacks

Source: https://context7.com/google/adk-go/llms.txt

LLM agents support callbacks for inspecting, logging, caching, and modifying model requests and responses. The `BeforeModelCallbacks` allow you to intercept the model request before it's sent. This is useful for implementing caching, where you can check if a response already exists for the given request and return it directly, skipping the actual model call. If no cached response is found, you can return `nil, nil` to proceed with the model call.

The `AfterModelCallbacks` are executed after the model has responded. Here, you can inspect the response, log token usage, or modify the response before it's returned to the user. For example, you can cache the successful response for future use. Error handling is also crucial, and `OnModelErrorCallbacks` allow you to gracefully manage and potentially recover from errors that occur during the model interaction.

